11 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
12 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
13 Article – Tax – General
14 10–758.
15 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
16 INDICATED.
17 (2) “DEPARTMENT” MEANS THE DEPARTMENT OF EMERGENCY
18 MANAGEMENT.
19 (3) “EMPLOYEE RETIREMENT SYSTEM” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN
20 § 10–209(A) OF THIS TITLE.
21 (4) “9–1–1 SPECIALIST” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 9–262(A) OF
22 THE TAX – PROPERTY ARTICLE.
23 (5) “SECRETARY” MEANS THE SECRETARY OF EMERGENCY
24 MANAGEMENT.
25 (B) (1) FOR TAXABLE YEARS BEGINNING AFTER DECEMBER 31, 2025,
26 BUT BEFORE JANUARY 1, 2029, AN INDIVIDUAL WHO IS A RETIRED 9–1–1 SPECIALIST
27 MAY CLAIM A CREDIT AGAINST THE STATE INCOME TAX IN THE AMOUNT STATED IN
28 THE TAX CREDIT CERTIFICATE APPROVED BY THE SECRETARY.
29 (2) THE INDIVIDUAL SHALL PROVIDE THE TAX CREDIT CERTIFICATE
30 TO THE COMPTROLLER, IN THE FORM AND MANNER REQUIRED BY THE
31 COMPTROLLER.
32 (C) (1) AN INDIVIDUAL QUALIFIED FOR THE CREDIT UNDER THIS
33 SECTION MAY APPLY TO THE DEPARTMENT FOR A TAX CREDIT CERTIFICATE.

HOUSE BILL 13 3
1 (2) (I) THE SECRETARY SHALL APPROVE EACH APPLICATION
2 UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION THAT QUALIFIES FOR A TAX CREDIT
3 CERTIFICATE.
4 (II) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (4) OF THIS SUBSECTION, THE
5 DEPARTMENT SHALL ISSUE A TAX CREDIT CERTIFICATE TO THE QUALIFIED
6 INDIVIDUAL IN AN AMOUNT EQUAL TO 4.75% OF THE FIRST $15,000 OF RETIREMENT
7 INCOME FROM AN EMPLOYEE RETIREMENT SYSTEM ATTRIBUTABLE TO THE
8 INDIVIDUAL’S SERVICE AS A 9–1–1 SPECIALIST IN THE STATE, NOT TO EXCEED $700.
9 (3) THE SECRETARY SHALL:
10 (I) DETERMINE WHETHER THE INDIVIDUAL IS QUALIFIED FOR
11 THE CREDIT UNDER THIS SECTION; AND
12 (II) NOTIFY THE COMPTROLLER, IN THE FORM AND MANNER
13 REQUIRED BY THE COMPTROLLER, OF THE INDIVIDUALS TO WHOM THE
14 DEPARTMENT HAS ISSUED A TAX CREDIT CERTIFICATE UNDER THIS SECTION.
15 (4) (I) THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF THE TAX CREDIT CERTIFICATES
16 APPROVED BY THE SECRETARY MAY NOT EXCEED $250,000 FOR EACH TAXABLE
17 YEAR.
18 (II) IF THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF TAX CREDIT CERTIFICATES THE
19 DEPARTMENT IS REQUIRED TO APPROVE UNDER PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS
20 SUBSECTION EXCEEDS $250,000 IN A FISCAL YEAR, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ISSUE
21 TAX CREDIT CERTIFICATES TO QUALIFIED INDIVIDUALS ON A PRO RATA BASIS.
22 10–207.
23 (a) To the extent included in federal adjusted gross income, the amounts under
24 this section are subtracted from the federal adjusted gross income of a resident to determine
25 Maryland adjusted gross income.
26 (mm) (1) (i) In this subsection the following words have the meanings
27 indicated.
28 (ii) “Correctional officer” means an individual who:
29 1. was employed in:
30 A. a State correctional facility, as defined in § 1–101 of the
31 Correctional Services Article;

4 HOUSE BILL 13
1 B. a local correctional facility, as defined in § 1–101 of the
2 Correctional Services Article;
3 C. a juvenile facility included in § 9–226 of the Human
4 Services Article; or
5 D. a facility of the United States that is equivalent to a State
6 or local correctional facility or a juvenile facility included in § 9–226 of the Human Services
7 Article; and
8 2. is eligible to receive retirement income attributable to the
9 individual’s employment under item 1 of this subparagraph.
10 (iii) “Emergency services personnel” means emergency medical
11 technicians [or], paramedics, OR 9–1–1 SPECIALISTS.
12 (iv) “Employee retirement system” has the meaning stated under §
13 10–209(a) of this subtitle.
14 (V) “9–1–1 SPECIALIST” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN §
15 9–262(A) OF THE TAX – PROPERTY ARTICLE.
16 [(v)] (VI) “Public safety employee” means an individual who is a
17 retired correctional officer, law enforcement officer, or fire, rescue, or emergency services
18 personnel of the United States, the State, or a political subdivision of the State.
19 (2) The subtraction under subsection (a) of this section includes the first
20 $15,000 of income from an employee retirement system that is attributable to service as a
21 public safety employee, if the income is received by an individual who is at least 55 years
22 old on the last day of the taxable year.
23 Article – Tax – Property
24 9–262.
25 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
26 (3) “9–1–1 specialist” means an employee of a county public safety
27 answering point, or an employee working in a county safety answering point, whose duties
28 and responsibilities include:
29 (i) receiving and processing 9–1–1 requests for emergency
30 assistance;
31 (ii) other support functions directly related to 9–1–1 requests for
32 emergency assistance; or

HOUSE BILL 13 5
1 (iii) dispatching law enforcement officers, fire rescue services,
2 emergency medical services, and other public safety services to the scene of an emergency.
3 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, on or before December 1,
4 2028, the Department of Emergency Management shall report to the Governor and, in
5 accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, the General Assembly on:
6 (1) the number of retired 9–1–1 specialists to whom the Department issued
7 a tax credit certificate under § 10–758 of the Tax – General Article, as enacted by Section
8 1 of this Act, and the aggregate amount of the tax credit certificates issued for each
9 preceding taxable year; and
10 (2) the number of 9–1–1 specialists employed in the State who have vested
11 under an employee retirement system, as defined under § 10–209(a) of the Tax – General
12 Article.
13 SECTION 2. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
14 July 1, 2026, and shall be applicable to all taxable years beginning after December 31, 2025.
15 It shall remain effective for a period of 3 years and, at the end of June 30, 2029, this Act,
16 with no further action required by the General Assembly, shall be abrogated and of no
17 further force and effect.
Approved:
